        'guide.korean.intro': 'Korean cuisine is gaining worldwide attention for its fermentation culture and vegetable-centered healthy diet. Fermented foods like kimchi are known to support gut health, and stews and soups are the soul food of Koreans.',
        'guide.chinese.intro': 'Korean-Chinese cuisine is a unique genre that has adapted Chinese mainland dishes to Korean tastes. Jajangmyeon and jjamppong have established themselves as uniquely Korean food culture.',
        'guide.japanese.intro': 'Japanese cuisine is characterized by fresh ingredients and delicate cooking techniques. Washoku, registered as a UNESCO Intangible Cultural Heritage, emphasizes visual beauty to the point of being called \'food you eat with your eyes\'.',
        'guide.western.intro': 'Western foods like pasta, steak, and pizza have deeply integrated into everyday Korean dining. Enjoyed both as special occasion meals and everyday delivery food.',
        'guide.snack.intro': 'Bunsik is a uniquely Korean food category centered around flour-based foods. Affordable and filling, it\'s consistently loved by students and office workers.',
        'food.kimchi.desc': 'A spicy and savory stew made with well-fermented kimchi and pork (or tuna). Voted Korea\'s most-loved stew, it\'s rich in lactobacillus and vitamins from fermented kimchi. Pairs perfectly with rice for a hearty meal.',
        'food.doenjang.desc': 'A beloved soybean paste stew with tofu, zucchini, and mushrooms. Studies suggest fermented doenjang may have anti-cancer and immunity-boosting properties. Mild and healthy, loved by people of all ages.',
        'food.samgyeopsal.desc': 'Thick-sliced pork belly grilled on a tabletop grill, eaten wrapped in lettuce, perilla leaves, garlic, and ssamjang. The quintessential Korean group meal, hugely popular with foreigners too.',
        'food.bibimbap.desc': 'Rice topped with assorted vegetables, meat, egg, and gochujang, mixed before eating. A nutritionally balanced meal in one bowl with carbs, protein, and vitamins. Featured in CNN\'s Top 50 Most Delicious Foods in the World.',
        'food.jeyuk.desc': 'Pork stir-fried with a gochujang-based marinade. Nicknamed "rice stealer" for how perfectly it pairs with rice. Rich in protein and very filling â€” a popular dinner choice.',
        'food.samgyetang.desc': 'A whole young chicken stuffed with ginseng, glutinous rice, jujubes, and garlic, simmered for a long time. Traditionally eaten on Korea\'s hottest summer days (Boknal) to restore energy. Rich in ginseng saponins and chicken protein.',
        'food.jajang.desc': 'Noodles topped with a sauce made from chunjang (fermented black bean paste), pork, and vegetables. Known as Korea\'s national comfort food, traditionally eaten on moving day or graduation day. Characterized by its sweet and rich chunjang flavor.',
        'food.jjamppong.desc': 'A spicy seafood noodle soup made with stir-fried seafood and vegetables. Stands alongside jajangmyeon as one of the two pillars of Korean-Chinese cuisine. Rich in calcium and zinc from shrimp, squid, mussels, and more.',
        'food.tangsuyuk.desc': 'Crispy deep-fried pork served with a sweet and sour sauce. Famous for the "pour it vs. dip it" debate. The contrast between the crispy batter and the tangy sauce is its charm.',
        'food.sushi.desc': 'Vinegared rice topped with fresh fish or seafood. Made primarily with omega-3-rich fish like salmon and tuna. High-protein, low-calorie â€” popular with people watching their diet too.',
        'food.ramen.desc': 'Japanese noodles in a rich broth topped with chashu pork, egg, narutomaki, and nori. Varieties include tonkotsu (pork bone), miso, shoyu (soy sauce), and shio (salt) broths. The deep, rich broth has become very popular in Korea as well.',
        'food.tonkatsu.desc': 'Pork loin or tenderloin breaded in panko and deep-fried, served with sauce. A dish originating in late 19th-century Japan, adapting the Western schnitzel technique. Widely available in Korea from casual snack bars to specialized restaurants.',
        'food.pasta.desc': 'Italy\'s signature noodle dish enjoyed with cream, tomato, or oil-based sauces. Varieties include carbonara (cream), arrabbiata (spicy tomato), and aglio e olio (garlic & olive oil). The unsaturated fatty acids in olive oil are good for cardiovascular health.',
        'food.steak.desc': 'Thick-cut beef grilled to your preferred doneness â€” Rare, Medium Rare, Medium, or Well-done. Rich in protein and iron. The perfect meal for special occasions.',
        'food.pizza.desc': 'Italian dish of dough topped with tomato sauce, cheese, and various toppings, baked in an oven. Korean favorites include bulgogi pizza and sweet potato pizza. Great for sharing and one of the most popular delivery foods.',
        'food.tteokbokki.desc': 'Chewy rice cakes and fish cakes stir-fried in a gochujang sauce â€” Korea\'s iconic street food. Rose sauce and cream sauce variations have become trendy. Addictively chewy and spicy-sweet, best enjoyed with sundae and twigim.',
        'food.kimbap.desc': 'Rice seasoned with sesame oil and salt, wrapped in nori with spinach, carrots, radish, egg, fish cake, and ham. Nutritious, affordable, and ideal for packed lunches. Recent varieties include cheese, tuna, and bulgogi kimbap.',
        'food.ramyeon.desc': 'Instant noodles cooked in boiling water with seasoning packets. Since Samyang Foods first released ramyeon in Korea in 1963, it has become a national staple. Add egg, green onion, or cheese to enhance the flavor.',
